## Diagnosis

The ETRO essay renderer is faithfully converting every `**bold**` span in the source Markdown into `<strong>` tags, then rendering them with a visually heavy weight. The author used bold as **inline section labels / scan anchors** — a common Markdown habit that works in a plain-text reading environment but breaks badly in a typeset design system where bold already carries semantic meaning ("this word matters within a sentence"). 36 bold spans across 7 sections creates visual noise that flattens the hierarchy instead of reinforcing it.

The second complaint (unclear section separation / dirty hierarchy) is the same root cause seen from the other side: when *everything* is bold, the actual H2/H3 headings lose their contrast authority and the page reads as a flat field of emphasis.

**Anti-pattern:** AP-072 — *Semantic punctuation leakage* (source-format conventions imported verbatim into a presentation layer that has different typographic rules). Also touches EAP-027 — *Undifferentiated emphasis* (using a single weight signal for both structural labels and inline stress, destroying the contrast hierarchy).

---

## Root Cause

Two separate issues share the same origin:

1. **Scan-anchor bold spans** — strings like `Per user.`, `Scaffolding.`, `Key insight:` that the author bolded so they could skim the raw Markdown. They are *de-facto inline headings*, not emphasis.
2. **Missing section dividers** — the prose body component probably has no visual rhythm between sections beyond the heading itself (no rule, no extra spacing, no color shift), so once the headings lose contrast authority (because bold is everywhere), the sections blur.

---

## Fix

### 1 — Strip / restyle scan-anchor bold at the content layer

The cleanest fix is a **Markdown pre-processing transform** that detects the pattern and converts it to a styled `<span>` (or a semantic `<dt>`-style element) rather than `<strong>`.

**Pattern:** a `<strong>` whose text content ends with `.` or `:` and is the *first non-whitespace node* of its paragraph — i.e., it is a label, not mid-sentence emphasis.

Create a unified rich-text / Markdown post-processor:

```
src/
  utilities/
    prose-transforms/
      strip-scan-anchor-bold.ts   ← new
      index.ts                    ← re-export barrel
```

#### `src/utilities/prose-transforms/strip-scan-anchor-bold.ts`

```typescript
/**
 * Prose transform: strip-scan-anchor-bold
 *
 * Detects <strong> nodes that are used as inline section labels
 * ("Scaffolding.", "Per user:", "Key insight —") rather than as
 * mid-sentence emphasis, and replaces them with a semantically
 * neutral <span data-prose-label> so the design system can style
 * them differently (small-caps, muted, etc.) without the visual
 * weight of bold.
 *
 * Rule: a <strong> is a scan anchor when ALL of the following hold:
 *   1. Its trimmed text ends with  . : — or –
 *   2. It is the first non-whitespace child of its <p> parent, OR
 *      the entire <p> consists only of that <strong> node.
 */

import { visit } from 'unist-util-visit'
import type { Root, Strong, Parent, Text } from 'mdast'

const ANCHOR_TAIL = /[.:\u2014\u2013]\s*$/   // ends with  . : — –

function isTextNode(node: unknown): node is Text {
  return (node as any)?.type === 'text'
}

export function stripScanAnchorBold() {
  return (tree: Root) => {
    visit(tree, 'paragraph', (paragraph: Parent) => {
      // Find the first non-whitespace child
      const firstMeaningful = paragraph.children.find(
        (child) => !(isTextNode(child) && child.value.trim() === ''),
      )

      if (!firstMeaningful || firstMeaningful.type !== 'strong') return

      const strong = firstMeaningful as Strong
      // Collect all text inside the <strong>
      const innerText = strong.children
        .filter(isTextNode)
        .map((t) => t.value)
        .join('')
        .trim()

      if (!ANCHOR_TAIL.test(innerText)) return

      // Mutate: replace <strong> with <span data-prose-label>
      // mdast doesn't have a generic "span" node, so we use an
      // html node to emit the literal HTML.  (Works with remark-html
      // and rehype pipelines alike.)
      const labelHtml = `<span data-prose-label>${innerText}</span>`
      ;(firstMeaningful as any).type = 'html'
      ;(firstMeaningful as any).value = labelHtml
      // Remove children so remark doesn't try to re-process them
      delete (firstMeaningful as any).children
    })
  }
}
```

#### `src/utilities/prose-transforms/index.ts`

```typescript
export { stripScanAnchorBold } from './strip-scan-anchor-bold'
```

#### Wire it into your Markdown/rich-text pipeline

Find wherever the ETRO essay content is processed — most likely a `unified` / `remark` pipeline or a Payload `richText` renderer:

```typescript
// e.g. src/app/(frontend)/essays/[slug]/page.tsx  or
//      src/components/RichText/serialize.tsx

import { unified } from 'unified'
import remarkParse from 'remark-parse'
import remarkRehype from 'remark-rehype'
import rehypeStringify from 'rehype-stringify'
import { stripScanAnchorBold } from '@/utilities/prose-transforms'

const processor = unified()
  .use(remarkParse)
  .use(stripScanAnchorBold)          // ← insert before remarkRehype
  .use(remarkRehype, { allowDangerousHtml: true })
  .use(rehypeStringify, { allowDangerousHtml: true })
```

If you use Payload's Lexical rich-text serializer instead of remark, apply the equivalent transform in the node serializer (see step 3 below).

---

### 2 — Style `[data-prose-label]` as a small-caps / muted label

```css
/* src/styles/prose.css  (or wherever your Tailwind prose
   overrides live — import into globals.css) */

[data-prose-label] {
  /* Not bold — use weight, case, and color to signal "label" */
  display: inline;                    /* stays inline with text     */
  font-size: 0.6875rem;               /* 11 px at 16 px base        */
  font-weight: 500;
  letter-spacing: 0.08em;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--color-muted-foreground, oklch(55% 0 0));

  /* Tiny gap so the prose that follows breathes */
  margin-inline-end: 0.25em;
}
```

This gives the scan anchors a *different* visual language from both body text and headings — they read as metadata, not content.

---

### 3 — Restore section separation

Add a visible rhythm signal between H2 sections. The lightest touch that doesn't add decoration for its own sake:

```css
/* src/styles/prose.css */

.prose h2 {
  /* Extra top space creates the section break without a rule */
  margin-top: 3rem;          /* was probably 1.5–2rem */
  padding-top: 1.5rem;

  /* Subtle top rule — use the same muted token */
  border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border, oklch(88% 0 0));
}

/* First H2 shouldn't get the rule (it's right under the lede) */
.prose > h2:first-of-type {
  border-top: none;
  padding-top: 0;
}
```

Or in Tailwind:

```typescript
// tailwind.config.ts
typography: {
  DEFAULT: {
    css: {
      h2: {
        marginTop: '3rem',
        paddingTop: '1.5rem',
        borderTop: '1px solid var(--color-border)',
      },
    },
  },
},
```

---

### 4 — If using Payload Lexical (no remark pipeline)

Override the `bold` leaf serializer for the essay template specifically:

```typescript
// src/components/RichText/serialize.tsx

import type { SerializedLeafNode } from '@payloadcms/richtext-lexical'

// Inside your leaf serializer:
case 'bold': {
  const text = node.text.trim()
  const isScanAnchor = /[.:\u2014\u2013]\s*$/.test(text)

  if (isScanAnchor) {
    return (
      <span data-prose-label key={i}>
        {node.text}
      </span>
    )
  }

  return <strong key={i}>{node.text}</strong>
}
```

---

## Principle

> **Presentation layers must sanitize source-format conventions.**
> Markdown bold is a *scanning aid for the author*, not a typographic instruction. A design system's job is to map authorial intent (label, emphasis, stress) to its own visual vocabulary — not to pass raw markup signals through unchanged. When a single CSS property (`font-weight: bold`) must serve both "inline emphasis" and "section label", the hierarchy collapses. Separate the signals; give each a distinct but lightweight visual treatment; reserve `<strong>` for genuine mid-sentence stress only.
>
> Corollary: section separation should come from *spatial rhythm and structural markers* (heading size, top rule, generous margin), not from the density of bold text within the body.
